<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Nevada's exceptional solar resource makes it one of the most productive states for solar energy generation in the United States. The state receives an average of 5.6 peak sun hours per day, with southern Nevada areas like Las Vegas receiving up to 6.0 peak sun hours daily during optimal months. This abundant solar irradiance translates to higher energy production per installed kilowatt compared to most other states, allowing homeowners to generate more electricity with smaller system sizes.</p>

<p>The desert climate provides additional advantages for solar production, including low humidity levels that reduce atmospheric interference and minimal precipitation that could obstruct panels. Nevada's high altitude in many regions also contributes to increased solar efficiency, as panels perform better in the thinner atmosphere. A typical residential solar installation in Nevada can produce between 1,400 to 1,600 kilowatt-hours per year per installed kilowatt, significantly higher than the national average of 1,200-1,400 kWh per kW annually.</p>

<p>Seasonal variations in Nevada are relatively modest compared to northern states, with winter production typically dropping to about 60-70% of peak summer output. This consistent year-round production helps ensure steady returns on solar investments and more predictable energy savings. The state's solar resource quality is so strong that even rooftops with less than optimal orientation or slight shading can still produce economically viable amounts of electricity.</p>

