<h2>Nevada Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Nevada offers several attractive incentives for solar panel and HVAC system installations, making these upgrades more affordable for homeowners. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, then decreases to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the full cost of solar panel systems, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, representing substantial savings for Nevada homeowners investing in solar energy.</p>

<p>At the state level, Nevada offers a property tax abatement program for renewable energy systems, including solar installations. This abatement exempts the added value of solar systems from property tax assessments, ensuring that homeowners don't face increased property taxes due to their solar investments. The abatement applies for the useful life of the system, typically 20-25 years, providing long-term tax savings that enhance the overall return on investment.</p>

<p>NV Energy, the state's primary utility company, operates several programs that benefit solar and energy efficiency investments. Their net metering program allows solar customers to receive credit for excess electricity generated and fed back into the grid, though rates and terms have evolved over recent years. The utility also offers various rebate programs for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, with rebates ranging from \$200-\$1,500 depending on system efficiency ratings and type. Additionally, NV Energy provides energy audits and efficiency consultations that can help homeowners optimize their systems for maximum savings.</p>

<p>Local jurisdictions may offer additional incentives, with cities like Las Vegas and Reno occasionally providing expedited permitting processes or fee reductions for renewable energy and efficiency projects. The Nevada Governor's Office of Energy also periodically administers grant programs and special initiatives supporting residential clean energy adoption, particularly in underserved communities or for low-income households.</p>

